Here's the equivalent Java code for the given JavaScript function:

```java
public class Forecast {
    public static double forecast(double x, double[] ky, double[] kx) {
        int i = 0;
        double nr = 0, dr = 0, ax = 0, ay = 0, a = 0, b = 0;

        // Calculate average
        double sum = 0;
        for (i = 0; i < kx.length; i++) {
            sum += kx[i];
        }
        ax = sum / kx.length;

        sum = 0;
        for (i = 0; i < ky.length; i++) {
            sum += ky[i];
        }
        ay = sum / ky.length;

        // Calculate forecast
        for (i = 0; i < kx.length; i++) {
            nr += ((kx[i] - ax) * (ky[i] - ay));
            dr += Math.pow((kx[i] - ax), 2);
        }

        b = nr / dr;
        a = ay - b * ax;

        return (a + b * x);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example usage
        double[] kx = { /* Insert your values here */ };
        double[] ky = { /* Insert your values here */ };
        double x = /* Insert your value here */;

        double result = forecast(x, ky, kx);
        System.out.println("Forecast: " + result);
    }
}
```

Replace the placeholders with your actual data when using this code.